5000|$|If {{you need}} a {{centrifugal}} force to explain what you see, then you are rotating. Newton's conclusion was that rotation is absolute. Other thinkers suggest that pure logic implies only relative rotation makes sense. For example, Bishop Berkeley and Ernst Mach (among others) suggested that it is relative rotation {{with respect to the}} <b>fixed</b> <b>stars</b> that matters, and rotation of the <b>fixed</b> <b>stars</b> relative to an object has the same effect as rotation of the object with respect to the <b>fixed</b> <b>stars.</b> [...] Newton's arguments do not settle this issue; his arguments may be viewed, however, as establishing centrifugal force as a basis for an operational definition of what we actually mean by absolute rotation.|$|R
